  "prompt": "What books should Computer Science students read before they start their MS in US Universities?",
  "response": "Here are some recommended books for Computer Science students preparing for an MS in US Universities:\n\nTechnical Fundamentals:\n1. \"Introduction to Algorithms\" by Cormen, Leiserson, Rivest, and Stein\n2. \"Design Patterns\" by Gang of Four\n3. \"Clean Code\" by Robert Martin\n4. \"Computer Systems: A Programmer's Perspective\" by Bryant and O'Hallaron\n\nProgramming Languages:\n1. \"Effective Java\" by Joshua Bloch\n2. \"Python Crash Course\" by Eric Matthes\n3. \"JavaScript: The Good Parts\" by Douglas Crockford\n\nMathematics:\n1. \"Discrete Mathematics and Its Applications\" by Kenneth Rosen\n2. \"Linear Algebra and Its Applications\" by Gilbert Strang\n\nResearch and Academic Skills:\n1. \"A PhD is Not Enough\" by Peter Feibelman\n2. \"How to Read a Paper\" by Srinivasan Keshav\n\nSpecialized Areas:\n1. Machine Learning: \"Introduction to Machine Learning\" by Ethem Alpaydin\n2. Data Science: \"Python for Data Analysis\" by Wes McKinney\n3. Cybersecurity: \"The Web Application Hacker's Handbook\"\n\nSoft Skills:\n1. \"Pragmatic Programmer\" by Andrew Hunt\n2. \"Soft Skills\" by John Sonmez\n\nThese books will provide a strong foundation across various CS domains.",
